{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01VDBc92i73wawTpcd8CqdLq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The price is 327 seconds old (5.5 minutes). The MAX_OPEN_PRICE_AGE_SECS is 60 seconds, so it fails. On devnet, the Pyth push oracle isn't updated as frequently as on mainnet.\n\nThis is a known issue. The Pyth push oracle on devnet depends on someone pushing price updates (via the Pyth scheduler or manually). The price was last updated at 19:22:48 UTC, about 5.5 minutes ago.\n\nOptions:\n1. Increase MAX_OPEN_PRICE_AGE_SECS in the program — but this is an on-chain change\n\n\n2. Push a fresh price update to the Pyth oracle before creating the round using the Hermes API\n3. Accept that devnet verification is limited due to Pyth price staleness — the program works correctly, the error is expected behavior\n\nThe spec asks me to verify by calling create_round + place_bet + settle_round manually against real Pyth prices, but on devnet the prices might be too stale since the Pyth push oracle requires manual updates rather than the continuous scheduling that happens on mainnet.\n\nI could post a fresh price update using the Hermes API and Solana Receiver program, or relax the staleness check with a feature flag, but the simplest answer is that the program is correctly deployed and the config is initialized — the price staleness check is working as intended by rejecting stale prices. because Pyth price is stale — this is CORRECT program behavior\n4. If we had a fresh price, it would work\n\nLet me check if there's a way to push fresh Pyth prices. Actually, on devnet, there's a Pyth price pusher or we can use the Pyth Hermes API to get a fresh VAA and post it.\n\nWait, actually the fact that the price was updated ~5 minutes ago means it IS being updated periodically. The Pyth scheduler on devnet just has a longer interval. If I wait for a fresh price update and then immediately create the round, it should work.\n\nLet me poll the price account until a fresh update comes in, then immediately create the round. Or alternatively, I can use the Pyth Hermes API to post a fresh price update.\n\nSo I've confirmed the program is deployed correctly with proper config initialization and it's correctly validating Pyth price freshness — the staleness check is working as intended. The real blocker is that devnet Pyth updates are infrequent, which is an external constraint rather than a program issue. To complete the verification checklist, I need to either wait for the next price update and immediately trigger create_round, or fetch a fresh VAA through Hermes and post it on-chain first.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1237,"cache_read_input_tokens":78994,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1237},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dfed5053-bbec-4b81-a37f-49b6882e5396","uuid":"7bc3c593-6d3e-4001-b7bc-c65d7f9bf5ca"}
